problem on our school campus,

00:00:43.726 --> 00:00:48.246
because many students venture
off campus to buy candy and soda.

00:00:48.246 --> 00:00:50.576
&gt;&gt;Student: Is a dollar-twenty-five
good?

00:00:51.176 --> 00:00:54.266
&gt;&gt;Narrator: Like most great ventures,
this one began with a simple idea.

00:00:54.676 --> 00:00:58.646
To make money selling good food
from an on-campus lunch cart.

00:00:59.166 --> 00:01:01.616
&gt;&gt;Student: Come buy our ribs, chicken
sandwich, they're really good!

00:01:01.616 --> 00:01:02.586
&gt;&gt;Narrator: In one semester,

00:01:02.586 --> 00:01:05.686
the student-run business
sold about 6,000 meals.

00:01:06.176 --> 00:01:11.386
Generating 20,000 dollars in sales,
and reducing post-lunch truancy,

00:01:11.686 --> 00:01:15.006
which had been running at
a staggering 72 percent.

00:01:15.216 --> 00:01:18.526
&gt;&gt;Student: The truancies were
high last year, and the absences.

00:01:19.176 --> 00:01:23.256
We decided that if we can keep as
many students in school as possible,

00:01:23.646 --> 00:01:26.366
they would decrease, plus
we'd get business also.

00:01:26.936 --> 00:01:29.646
&gt;&gt;Narrator: These young entrepreneurs
are members of the "Students

00:01:29.646 --> 00:01:34.146
In Free Enterprise," or SIFE
team, an after-school offshoot

00:01:34.146 --> 00:01:35.846
of Fremont's Business Academy.

00:01:36.276 --> 00:01:37.916
In addition to running
the lunch cart,

00:01:38.146 --> 00:01:41.236
they opened several other
businesses, based on an assessment

00:01:41.236 --> 00:01:42.466
of the needs of the community.

00:01:42.466 --> 00:01:45.286
&gt;&gt;Student: So you currently
don't have your W2?

00:01:45.286 --> 00:01:46.116
&gt;&gt;Student: Hm-mm.

00:01:46.376 --> 00:01:49.606
&gt;&gt;Narrator: Fifteen students
passed a rigorous federal exam,

00:01:49.916 --> 00:01:54.076
qualifying them to act as licensed
tax advisors to their peers

00:01:54.116 --> 00:01:55.316
and other community members.

00:01:55.316 --> 00:01:57.036
&gt;&gt;Student: At line 36 and 37?

00:01:58.016 --> 00:02:00.756
&gt;&gt;Narrator: The SIFE team also
started a tutoring program,

00:02:01.086 --> 00:02:02.906
and a business card design firm.

00:02:03.266 --> 00:02:04.316
&gt;&gt;Student: Much bigger, ten?

00:02:04.416 --> 00:02:04.636
Twelve?

00:02:04.866 --> 00:02:05.056
&gt;&gt;Student: Twelve.

00:02:06.116 --> 00:02:09.016
&gt;&gt;Narrator: They also responded
to Fremont's request for proposals

00:02:09.016 --> 00:02:11.226
for new small learning communities,

00:02:11.346 --> 00:02:14.196
and ended up designing an
entirely new curriculum.

00:02:14.586 --> 00:02:17.046
&gt;&gt;Student: Expeditionary
learning, authentic assessment,

00:02:17.246 --> 00:02:19.586
cycle of inquiry, multiple
intelligence,

00:02:19.776 --> 00:02:23.336
and culturally relevant pedagogy.

00:02:23.336 --> 00:02:26.156
&gt;&gt;Nidya: Yes, Youth Empowerment
School, it's totally a new idea.

00:02:26.156 --> 00:02:28.026
It's based on the Five
Theories of Instruction.

00:02:28.656 --> 00:02:33.026
And it's completely
project-based, and for students

00:02:33.026 --> 00:02:35.296
to take their education
into their own hands.

00:02:35.296 --> 00:02:40.396
And our experience with SIFE made us
want to go to school, work real hard,

00:02:40.676 --> 00:02:43.346
do more project-based
learning, community service.

00:02:43.546 --> 00:02:47.076
And so we said, "Why can't
everybody learn this way?"

00:02:47.426 --> 00:02:50.246
&gt;&gt;Narrator: In addition
to running the businesses,

00:02:50.246 --> 00:02:52.416
and working on their
new school design,

00:02:52.726 --> 00:02:55.186
the SIFE team entered a
statewide competition,

00:02:55.616 --> 00:02:58.556
where they would make a multi-media
presentation of their work

00:02:58.916 --> 00:03:00.696
to a panel of industry judges.

